{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/superficial-vein-thrombosis-superficial-thrombophlebitis/background-information/complications/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"b23bb9bc-355d-5db3-909c-ba53a4e4ed95","slug":"complications","fullItemName":"Complications","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field ff7d8025-304c-4fc9-9732-5202fb5e0938 --><h2>What are the complications?</h2><!-- end field ff7d8025-304c-4fc9-9732-5202fb5e0938 -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 3b9dab7a-d9c4-494e-9cd3-ec9e3dcefb0e --><!-- begin field bd4173e0-2291-4206-a55f-af74b66d396c --><ul><li><strong>De</strong><strong>ep vein thrombosis (DVT) or pulmonary embolism (PE)</strong> <strong>may develop in association with superficial vein thrombosis.</strong><ul><li>The reported prevalence of concurrent DVT varies widely from 2.6%–65% [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/superficial-vein-thrombosis-superficial-thrombophlebitis/references/\">National Clinical Guideline Centre, 2013</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/superficial-vein-thrombosis-superficial-thrombophlebitis/references/\">BMJ, 2015</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/superficial-vein-thrombosis-superficial-thrombophlebitis/references/\">Di Minno, 2016</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/superficial-vein-thrombosis-superficial-thrombophlebitis/references/\">BMJ, 2018</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/superficial-vein-thrombosis-superficial-thrombophlebitis/references/\">Almeida, 2019</a>], and the prevalence of concurrent PE is between 0.5%–6.9% [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/superficial-vein-thrombosis-superficial-thrombophlebitis/references/\">Di Minno, 2016</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/superficial-vein-thrombosis-superficial-thrombophlebitis/references/\">BMJ, 2018</a>].</li><li>The risk of DVT is greater in people with superficial vein thrombosis if [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/superficial-vein-thrombosis-superficial-thrombophlebitis/references/\">BMJ, 2018</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/superficial-vein-thrombosis-superficial-thrombophlebitis/references/\">Geersing, 2018</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/superficial-vein-thrombosis-superficial-thrombophlebitis/references/\">Almeida, 2019</a>]:<ul><li>The superficial thrombus extends near where the affected superficial vein joins the deep veins, for example where the long saphenous vein joins the femoral vein at the groin. Superficial vein thrombosis of the long saphenous vein within 3 cm of the saphenofemoral junction is considered to be equivalent to a DVT [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/superficial-vein-thrombosis-superficial-thrombophlebitis/references/\">Cosmi, 2015</a>].</li><li>The superficial thrombus is 5 cm or greater in length.</li><li>The person has reduced mobility.</li><li>The superficial thrombus is not associated with varicose veins.</li><li>There is a past history of DVT or PE.</li><li>The person has active cancer [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/superficial-vein-thrombosis-superficial-thrombophlebitis/references/\">Barco, 2017</a>].</li></ul></li></ul></li><li><strong>Other possible complications include </strong>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/superficial-vein-thrombosis-superficial-thrombophlebitis/references/\">BMJ, 2018</a>]<strong>:</strong><ul><li>Infection — septic (infected) thrombophlebitis may occur, usually when superficial vein thrombosis is the result of vein instrumentation or cannulation. Although infected thrombophlebitis most commonly presents as a localized infection, it may spread (especially in this group of people) and become life threatening [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/superficial-vein-thrombosis-superficial-thrombophlebitis/references/\">Rosh, 2014</a>].</li><li>Skin changes — hyperpigmentation and/or a persistent firm subcutaneous nodule may occur at the affected site.</li><li>Varicose veins — can develop if the valves are damaged during recanalization of the thrombosed vein.</li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field bd4173e0-2291-4206-a55f-af74b66d396c --><!-- end item 3b9dab7a-d9c4-494e-9cd3-ec9e3dcefb0e -->","topic":{"id":"07820562-ab2f-5ea0-9097-3e6e5a62bec4","topicId":"3c0e3637-8623-4aa4-9bdf-83c4ead61135","topicName":"Superficial vein thrombosis (superficial thrombophlebitis)","slug":"superficial-vein-thrombosis-superficial-thrombophlebitis","lastRevised":"Last revised in March 2020","chapters":[{"id":"a5f3a42e-3e23-59d7-83fb-fd26995ebf74","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"1ceec510-5b3b-59b2-be08-fde928defc1e","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","subChapters":[]},{"id":"8b0cc395-7b80-5e19-a891-b27b1d88c9f3","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","subChapters":[{"id":"75c7c081-3b2a-5f62-aead-766ba5534a36","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"fcc6e0b2-bfab-56d2-a1e0-57e5f3f6c19a","slug":"update","fullItemName":"Update"}]},{"id":"6da7aa90-c506-5e57-baed-74b22c09af0a","fullItemName":"Goals and outcome measures","slug":"goals-outcome-measures","subChapters":[{"id":"8a802f98-487d-5c7e-829e-4a9e669fe875","slug":"goals","fullItemName":"Goals"},{"id":"7dff5216-bc4a-529e-854f-a128cb8b54ca","slug":"outcome-measures","fullItemName":"Outcome measures"},{"id":"999e411a-0346-5c64-aa2d-eba133633715","slug":"audit-criteria","fullItemName":"Audit criteria"},{"id":"fed9fa0e-2eb0-5385-b244-1efe9fad43ce","slu